# Vaping Products Duty (VPD)

<%= partial 'documentation/partials/google_tag_manager_js' %>

From 1 October 2026, the Vaping Products Duty (VPD) changes described in this documentation apply to movements of vaping products.

If your software supports these movements, update it before 1 October 2026 to ensure it remains compatible with the Excise Movement and Control System (EMCS).


## Busines Codelists

| Number   | Title                | Format |
| -------- | -------------------- | ------ |
| HMRCBC36 | Vaping EPC code V000 | an4    |
| HMRCBC37 | Vaping CN Codes      | n8     |


## Busines Rules

### VPDBR01

This message cannot be processed as vaping product destination type can only be a Tax warehouse or an Export.


### VPDBR02

Vaping products from Northern Ireland to an EU Tax warehouse, or from the EU to a Northern Ireland Tax warehouse cannot be mixed with other products.


### VPDBR03

The NI Consignee ID must be the same as the Consignor ID on the movement when an NI Consignee creates a vaping movement on behalf of the EU Consignor.


## Process flows

### Northern Ireland to EU movement of vaping products

<a href="../images/Vaping-Products-Duty-NI-to-EU.png" target="_blank"><img src="../images/Vaping-Products-Duty-NI-to-EU.png" alt="A process map describing the movement of vaping products from Northern Ireland to an EU member state"></a>
<a href="../images/Vaping-Products-Duty-NI-to-EU.png" target="_blank">Open process map in a new tab.</a>

This process describes the movement of vaping products from Northern Ireland to an EU member state.

Vaping products from Northern Ireland to an EU Tax warehouse, or from the EU to a Northern Ireland Tax warehouse cannot be mixed with other products.

According to this scenario, the consignor submits a draft e-AD (IE815: N_EAD_SUB) to the MSA dispatch application containing only the vaping product details of the movement. The draft e-AD (IE815: N_EAD_SUB) must contain only vaping products and include the movement guarantee, the consignee details, the destination EU member state and the place of delivery.

Upon receiving the draft e-AD (IE815: N_EAD_SUB), the MSA dispatch application performs the required validations before forwarding the draft e-AD to EMCS:

- If validation is successful, the movement is accepted and the MSA dispatch application issues an e-AD (IE801: C_EAD_VAL) confirming that the movement has been registered.
- If validation is unsuccessful, a Generic Refusal Message (IE704: N_REJ_DAT) is generated by the EMCS service. This happens when an incoming message has successfully passed XML schema validation, but fails one or more business rule validations. It provides structured information describing why the submitted message cannot be processed.

Before the goods are dispatched, the Northern Ireland trader may amend the place of delivery by submitting an update message (IE813: C_UPD_DAT):

- If the destination remains within the EU, the movement continues as a vaping products movement.
- If the destination changes to a non-EU destination, the movement follows the standard EMCS process applicable to the new destination.

The Northern Ireland trader may also cancel the movement by submitting a cancellation message (IE810: C_CAN_DAT), subject to the standard EMCS business rules

Unlike alcohol and tobacco movements, the movement is not closed by the EU consignee because Vaping Products Duty applies only within the UK.

Any movement that remains open is automatically closed after 18 months.


### EU to Northern Ireland movement of vaping products

<a href="../images/Vaping-Products-Duty-EU-to-NI.png" target="_blank"><img src="../images/Vaping-Products-Duty-EU-to-NI.png" alt="A process map describing the movement of vaping products from an EU member state to Northern Ireland"></a>
<a href="../images/Vaping-Products-Duty-EU-to-NI.png" target="_blank">Open process map in a new tab.</a>

This process describes the movement of vaping products from an EU member state to Northern Ireland.

Vaping products from Northern Ireland to an EU Tax warehouse, or from the EU to a Northern Ireland Tax warehouse cannot be mixed with other products.

According to this scenario, the Northern Ireland trader submits a draft e-AD (IE815: N_EAD_SUB) to create the movement. The draft e-AD (IE815: N_EAD_SUB) must contain only vaping products and include the movement guarantee, the place of delivery in Northern Ireland and the originating EU member state.

Upon receiving the draft e-AD (IE815: N_EAD_SUB), the MSA dispatch application performs the required validations before forwarding the draft e-AD to EMCS:

- If validation is successful, the movement is accepted and the MSA dispatch application issues an e-AD (IE801: C_EAD_VAL) confirming that the movement has been registered.
- If validation is unsuccessful, a Generic Refusal Message (IE704: N_REJ_DAT) is generated by the EMCS service. This happens when an incoming message has successfully passed XML schema validation, but fails one or more business rule validations. It provides structured information describing why the submitted message cannot be processed.

Before the goods arrive, the Northern Ireland trader may amend the place of delivery by submitting an update message (IE813: C_UPD_DAT), provided that the goods continue to be delivered to a warehouse in Northern Ireland.

The Northern Ireland trader may also cancel the movement by submitting a cancellation message (IE810: C_CAN_DAT), subject to the standard EMCS business rules.

When the goods arrive in Northern Ireland, the consignee submits a draft Report of Receipt (IE818: C_DEL_DAT). The movement guarantee is discharged and the movement is closed using the standard EMCS process.
